HT|b|cs|6|CP||FP|1|AT|^-{            Blackwood - Queen Ask            }
^-|
HT|d|FP||AT|^c@2If partner responds 5@C or 5@D, and you do not have the Queen of trumps, you often would like to know if partner has it. The way you ask for the Queen is to bid the next higher suit over partner's response.|
PG| ***** 1 ***** |


AT| For examples in the auction below 5@D bid by 4NT bidder,
|HT|h|cs|6|AT|^C{|ia|,1dp1hp3hp4np5cp!5d|at|} |
PG| ***** 2 ***** |


HT|g|AT|^N@2^Y@3is asking for trump queen by bidding, the next higher bid, |
PG| ***** 3 ***** |


AT|and in the this|HT|n|AT|^C{|ia|,1dp1sp3sp4np5dp!5h|at|} |
PG| ***** 4 ***** |


HT|m|AT|^N@2^z@3auction 4NT bidder is asking for trump queen by bidding 5@H which is next higher bid. The only exception is that if the next higher suit is the agreed upon trump, then you skip the trump suit. |
PG| ***** 5 ***** |


HT|u|AT|
^C@2Therefore, 4NT bidder, playing RKC has two bids to inquire for trump Queen--5@D and 5@H. As you already know in either 1430 or 0314 the 5@H response denies holding trump queen and and 5@S confirms holding the trump queen or assure partner that there is a 10-card fit. Yes, if partner asks for Queen and you have 10-card fit (that is as good as having the Queen of trumps) you should respond as if you have the Queen of trump even if you do not have it.|
PG| ***** 6 ***** |


NT||
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
HT|b|cs|6|CP||FP|2|AT|^-{            Responding to Queen Ask            }
^-|
HT|c|cp||FP||AT|^c@2The following is how you respond to Queen ask by the 4NTrumper.:|
PG| ***** 7 ***** |


AT|
- if you do not have the Queen of trumps, you bid 5 of the agreed upon trump suit. Therefore, in this auction,
|HT|e|cs|6|Va|8|AT|{|ia|,1Dp1Hp3Hp4Np5Cp5Dp!5H|at|}|
PG| ***** 8 ***** |


HT|e|AT|^N@2^Y@3auction 5@H denies holding the Queen of trumps.|
PG| ***** 9 ***** |


HT|m|AT|^C@2
- if you do have the Queen of trumps, then you bid your cheapest King outside the trump suit.|
PG| ***** 10 ***** |


AT| Then, in this
|HT|p|AT|{|ia|,1Dp1Hp3Hp4Np5Cp5Dp!6C|at|} |HT|o|AT|^N@2^Y@3auction 6@C says the Blackwood responder has the Queen of trumps and the King of clubs (but not the King of spades).|
PG| ***** 11 ***** |


NT||
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
HT|b|cs|6|CP||FP|2|AT|^-{            Blackwood - Queen Ask            }
^-|HT|d|fp||AT|^C@2If you have the Queen of trumps but no outside King, then you bid 5N (some people, including Bergen, play you bid 6 of your suit). So, in the next auction,|
PG| ***** 12 ***** |


HT|f|cs|6|AT|{|ia|,1Dp1Hp3Hp4Np5Cp!5Dp!5N|at|} |
PG| ***** 13 ***** |


HT|e|AT|^N@2^Y@35N says that the Blackwood responder has the Queen of trumps but no outside Kings.|
PG| ***** 14 ***** |


HT|o|AT|^C@2One other caveat. On the rare occasions where your outside King is higher than the trump suit at the six level, you just bid 6 of your agreed upon trump suit. Because you don't want to go past six.|
PG| ***** 15 ***** |


AT|

Let me show you examples of the Queen ask.|
PG| ***** 16 ***** |


NT||
