{            Blackwood - Queen Ask            }
^-|ht|e|fp||at|^c@2You are South and holding the hand on the right|
ht|i|va|6|cs|6|at|^B{|ia|,1sp2np4np5cp5dp?|at|} ^mBoard 15|HT|i|cs|1|at|^p{|ih|pSAQ76HK9876D95CK5|at|}|ht|o|at|^rSouth Hand|hf|O|cq||lb|*BNow, what bid would you make?^^5h|HT|Q|cp|8|AT|
^B@2^Y@3^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||fp||at|5@H is the correct answer. 5@D is asking about the Queen of spades, since you have it, you bid 5@H, your cheapest King. The rule is you make the cheapest bid you can make to show your King. And 5H is certainly cheaper than 6C. Granted, the example is unusual in that it is rare you can show your cheapest King without forcing the hand to slam, but the rule still applies. If you bid 6C, you are denying the K of hearts. It is really no different in concept than control bidding, where if the auction goes, for example, 1D-1H-3H, your cheapest control bid is 3S (not 4C), and if you bid 4C, you are denying a spade control.

|HT|P|AT|^p^*BThis hand is worth  |cp|8|AT|(15)|CP||AT|  Dummy Points.^*N 
|ht|i|va|6|cs|6|at|^B{|ia|,1sp2np4np5cp5dp!5h|at|}|
